----field----
field: {446A339B-E1D9-4DE1-8B5E-DB7942EF1723}
name: Body
key: body
content-length: 1147

<p>Verastem Inc. is slashing its head count by 50%, or 20 employees, as the company continues to regroup after lead drug candidate VS-6063 failed to show an efficacy benefit for mesothelioma patients at an interim analysis in a Phase II clinical trial.</p><p>Boston-based Verastem isn't short on funds, since it had $132.1m in cash as of the end of the second quarter of 2015, but the company's layoffs will save $4.9m in annual employee-related costs after it spends $825,000 on one-time severance payments and job search assistance. Given the recent decline in biotechnology stocks generally and last month's sharp drop in Verastem's share value, it's probably wise for the company to hold on to its cash for ongoing early-stage development programs.</p><p>Verastem's stock price fell 2.5% to close at $1.93 per share on Oct. 9 after the layoffs were announced. The company's share price is trading 67% lower than its value on Sept. 25 &ndash; one business day before Verastem announced its <a href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/Can-Verastem-Recover-After-Failure-360710" target="_new">Phase II mesothelioma failure</a>.</p><p><p><p><p>
